<m0>from Germany, the United Kingdom and France (--) accounted for the highest first quarter of the decade.<ep>
  Nearly 202,000 Canadians (--) a 33.9 percent boost (--) surpassed 1993 highs, due in part to expanded flights, a more stable Canadian dollar and easing of health insurance concerns.<ep>
  Tourism from South America, Dade's top market in the region, grew 5.4 percent to 392,000 visitors. Tourism from Central America grew 29 percent to more than 89,000 visitors, though traffic from Mexico dropped 16.6 percent because of that country's economic difficulties.<ep>
  Economic problems from an active hurricane season accounted for a 48.5 percent drop in Caribbean visitors.<ep>
  The Greater Fort Lauderdale Convention & Visitors Bureau expects to release its first-quarter statistics next week.<ql>
